{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Saqaliya\" (addressing Sicily), the poet voices a lament for the grave of Hejazi (Arab Muslim) civilization on the island—once a vibrant cradle of that conquering desert nation's culture, now in ruins.[^1][^2]\n\nThe poem evokes the lost glory of those whose ships mastered the seas, whose swords renewed the world, and whose Takbir echoed thunderously, contrasting it with prior poetic laments for fallen Muslim centers like Baghdad, Delhi (Jahanabad), and Granada.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 \"Saqaliya\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 \"Saqaliya\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e#p-13e58a#p-ac137c#p-82cbe3).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 \"Saqaliya\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-02c3ef#p-83813c).",
